<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="260" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,977]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,628,653]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blume" authorityYear="1850" box="[687,816,628,652]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nothofagaceae" genus="Nothofagus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[687,816,628,652]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Nothofagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forests of 
<collectingRegion box="[942,1062,629,653]" country="Argentina" name="Rio Negro" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Río Negro</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1120,1311,628,653]" country="Argentina" name="Tierra del Fuego - Antartida e Islas del Atlantico Sur" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Tierra del Fuego</collectingRegion>
provinces, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,265,664,689]" name="Argentina" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, and on Wollaston Island, 
<collectingCountry box="[561,621,664,689]" name="Chile" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Chile</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[637,721,664,689]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1234,1256]" captionTargetBox="[267,1325,252,1118]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[205,1396,196,1194]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 35. Map of Argentine and Chilean Patagonia with distribution records of: Austrohelea shannoni (Wirth &amp; Blanton), green circles. Austrohelea sirii n. sp., yellow triangles. Austrohelea spinosa n. sp., red diamonds." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/806131/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="260" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,977]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,700,725]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirth" box="[808,1081,700,725]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" refString="Wirth, W. W. &amp; Blanton, F. S. (1972) A new Patagonian biting midge of the genus Monohelea, Isthmohelea (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Florida Entomologist, 55, 173 - 176." type="journal article" year="1972">Wirth &amp; Blanton (1972)</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of a single female from Bariloche, 
<collectingRegion box="[336,559,736,761]" country="Argentina" name="Rio Negro" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Río Negro province</collectingRegion>
in northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[749,860,736,761]" name="Argentina" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Argentine</collectingCountry>
Patagonia. In their book on the predaceous midges of the World, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirth" box="[307,575,772,797]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" refString="Wirth, W. W. &amp; Grogan, W. L. Jr. (1988) The predaceous midges of the World (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae; Tribe Ceratopogonini). In: Flora and Fauna Handbook 4. E. J. Brill, New York, pp. 1 - 160." type="journal article" year="1988">Wirth &amp; Grogan (1988)</bibRefCitation>
provided a generic diagnosis, the first description and data on males as well as illustrations of both sexes based on specimens from Wollaston Island, which is located at the extreme southeastern-most tip of 
<collectingCountry box="[428,489,844,869]" name="Chile" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Chile</collectingCountry>
south of the Beagle channel. We examined specimens from Bariloche and the Island of 
<collectingRegion box="[181,369,880,905]" country="Argentina" name="Tierra del Fuego - Antartida e Islas del Atlantico Sur" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Tierra del Fuego</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[380,494,880,905]" name="Argentina" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, and also from Wollaston Island, 
<collectingCountry box="[867,930,880,905]" name="Chile" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Chile</collectingCountry>
, and therefore, we confirm the validity of the sex association assumed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirth" box="[478,756,916,941]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" refString="Wirth, W. W. &amp; Grogan, W. L. Jr. (1988) The predaceous midges of the World (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae; Tribe Ceratopogonini). In: Flora and Fauna Handbook 4. E. J. Brill, New York, pp. 1 - 160." type="journal article" year="1988">Wirth &amp; Grogan (1988)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wirth &amp; Grogan" authorityYear="1988" baseAuthorityName="Wirth &amp; Blanton" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[769,1016,916,940]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Austrohelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shannoni">
<emphasis box="[769,1016,916,940]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">Austrohelea shannoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ronderos &amp; Spinelli &amp; Grogan, 2017" authorityName="Ronderos &amp; Spinelli &amp; Grogan" authorityYear="2017" box="[1240,1360,917,940]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Austrohelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1240,1257,917,940]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1274,1360,917,940]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1370,1436,916,941]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1370,1436,916,941]" pageId="5" pageNumber="260">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
Characters to distinguish both species are in the key and the discussion section of the latter species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
